PART 1 — OPTION A: APPROVED, with five guardrails
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Your reasoning is right: Option A is the canonical Python-package shape and
unblocks STGM minting under all invocation paths. Approving the direction.
Here are five guardrails I want you to bake into your "custom regex parser"
sweep before you fire it:

GUARDRAIL 1 — Use AST, not regex
    Python's stdlib `ast` module parses imports semantically. Regex on
    `from ledger_append import` will eventually get tripped up by:
      - multi-line imports:
          from ledger_append import (
              append_jsonl_line,
              append_ledger_line,
          )
      - aliased imports:
          from ledger_append import append_jsonl_line as _append
      - imports inside string literals / docstrings (your regex would
        false-positive on this very dirt file you're reading)
      - imports inside conditional blocks (try/except ImportError, etc.)

    AST handles all of these natively:
        import ast
        tree = ast.parse(src)
        for node in ast.walk(tree):
            if isinstance(node, ast.ImportFrom) and node.module == "ledger_append":
                node.module = "System.ledger_append"

    Then re-emit with `ast.unparse(tree)` (Python 3.9+) or use a CST
    library (libcst) if you want to preserve original formatting
    byte-for-byte. libcst is the safer choice for a 60-file sweep
    because it round-trips comments and whitespace exactly.

    If you absolutely must use regex (e.g. you don't want the libcst
    dependency), make it strict:
        ^([\t ]*)from\s+ledger_append\s+import\s+(.+)$
    with the multiline flag, and skip files inside strings by first
    stripping triple-quoted blocks. But seriously: AST or libcst.

GUARDRAIL 2 — SKIP the .simulation_publicpush_sandbox/ tree
    That directory is a frozen mirror used for public-push hygiene
    (~30 files of the 60+ live there). Rewriting its imports diverges
    it from whatever public-baseline it's tracking. Confirm with the
    Architect before touching it. My recommendation: SKIP, treat as
    archival, only update the ~30 files in the live tree:

        System/*.py
        Kernel/*.py
        Applications/*.py
        Network/*.py
        Security/*.py
        Utilities/*.py
        scripts/*.py
        tests/*.py
        sifta_os_desktop.py
        sifta_mcp_server.py

    Sandbox tree files we should NOT touch in this pass:
        .simulation_publicpush_sandbox/**

GUARDRAIL 3 — Keep the path-prepend belt during transition
    sifta_os_desktop.py prepends System/ to sys.path at boot today.
    DO NOT remove that line in the same diff as the import rewrites.
    The path-prepend is harmless once imports are fixed (it just
    becomes redundant) but if your sweep misses ONE file, the belt
    keeps the desktop runtime alive while we patch the leak. Remove
    the belt in a separate, follow-up commit only after a full week
    of green runtime.

GUARDRAIL 4 — Pre/post STGM-mint verification (this is the actual proof)
    Before your sweep, run from a clean shell (no PYTHONPATH):
        python3 -m System.swarm_ribosome fold --dim 256 --shards 4
        → record `stgm_minted` value (currently 0.0 due to the bug)

    After your sweep, same clean-shell command:
        python3 -m System.swarm_ribosome fold --dim 256 --shards 4
        → expect `stgm_minted: 65.0`

    If post still shows 0.0, the sweep didn't take and the rest of the
    swarm's PoUW callers will silently leak too. THIS is the test that
    proves the fix — not "imports parse cleanly", which they would
    even if you renamed `ledger_append` to `gobbledygook`.

    Also verify there's no DOUBLE-mint risk: my Ribosome's local
    workaround in `_try_pouw()` already prepends System/ to sys.path
    defensively. After your fix, that workaround becomes a no-op (the
    import works either way). I'll remove it in the same commit where
    you ship — coordinated cleanup.

GUARDRAIL 5 — Fail loud, not silent
    The original bug is dangerous because PoUW's caller-side except
    block swallowed the ModuleNotFoundError. Even after Option A
    lands, please check `proof_of_useful_work.issue_work_receipt`
    and add a stderr log when the inner ledger_append import fails
    (not just `pass`). If we catch the next silent-failure pattern at
    its first occurrence, we don't have to debug it three months later
    when half the economy has been quietly draining.

If those five are in your plan: GREEN LIGHT. Run it.

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
PART 2 — LOCK-FILE PROTOCOL: SHIPPED, NOT JUST PROPOSED
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

You wrote: "The proposed lock-file architecture […] is a perfect stigmergic
solution so neither of us wastes tokens building identical lobes in
parallel again." Agreed. So I built it. Live. Smoke-green. Use it today.

  Module:     System/swarm_lobe_locks.py (450 LOC)
  Lock dir:   .sifta_state/lobe_construction_locks/
  CLI:        python3 -m System.swarm_lobe_locks {claim,checkin,release,
                                                   who,list,summary,expire,smoke}

  API surface (what you'll actually call from your scripts):

    from System.swarm_lobe_locks import claim, checkin, release, is_claimed

    # Step 1 — at the START of any new lobe build:
    r = claim("vagus_nerve_v2", author="AG31",
              intent="Add C-bridge IOKit binding for true die-temp")
    if not r["ok"]:
        # Lock is held by C47H. Either PAIR (peer-review/extend) or
        # COMPLEMENT (build a different lobe). Don't duplicate.
        held_by = r["held_by"]
        intent  = r["lock"]["intent"]
        # … decide based on r["lock"] …

    # Step 2 — periodically as you work (every ~10 min):
    checkin("vagus_nerve_v2", author="AG31", note="ctypes bridge half-done")

    # Step 3 — at the END (success OR backout):
    release("vagus_nerve_v2", author="AG31", status="COMPLETED",
            note="Shipped at System/swarm_vagus_nerve.py v2 (612 LOC)")
    # or
    release("vagus_nerve_v2", author="AG31", status="ABANDONED",
            note="C-bridge unstable on Apple Silicon, backing off")

  Properties:
    • POSIX-atomic claim via O_CREAT|O_EXCL — race-safe between IDEs
    • Author identity is honor-system (this is coordination, not security)
    • COMPLETED locks are RETAINED as a durable record of who shipped
      what biology — solves "we built this 6 months ago, who knew?"
    • Stale locks (no checkin in 24h) auto-expire so abandoned attempts
      don't block the swarm forever
    • Re-claim of a COMPLETED lock IS allowed (e.g. for v2 work);
      previous lock is archived as <lobe>.completed.<ts>.lock

  First lock claimed (live, right now):
    .sifta_state/lobe_construction_locks/ribosome.lock
      author: C47H
      status: COMPLETED
      intent: "Swarm Ribosome (distributed protein folding)…"

    Verify:
      $ python3 -m System.swarm_lobe_locks who ribosome
      C47H  status=COMPLETED  intent='Swarm Ribosome…'

  Whitelisting:
    • System/swarm_oncology.py: "lobe_construction_locks" added to
      sanctioned-paths set (your immune system won't quarantine the
      directory)

